JDBC Steps

Every JDBC application follows these 7 steps.

1 Load Driver

2 Create Connection

3 Create Statement

4 Execute Query

5 Process Result

6 Close Resources

7 Exception Handling

Every real-time project follows this sequence.

CRUD Operations
Insert
String sql="insert into employee values(101,'Rahul',50000)";

Statement st=con.createStatement();

int rows=st.executeUpdate(sql);

System.out.println(rows+" Record Inserted");
Display
String sql="select * from employee";

Statement st=con.createStatement();

ResultSet rs=st.executeQuery(sql);

while(rs.next()){

System.out.println(
rs.getInt("id")+" "+
rs.getString("name")+" "+
rs.getDouble("salary"));

}
Update
String sql=
"update employee set salary=60000 where id=101";

Statement st=con.createStatement();

int rows=st.executeUpdate(sql);

System.out.println(rows+" Updated");
Delete
String sql=
"delete from employee where id=101";

Statement st=con.createStatement();

int rows=st.executeUpdate(sql);

System.out.println(rows+" Deleted");
Using PreparedStatement (Recommended)

In real-world applications, avoid concatenating user input into SQL. Use PreparedStatement to improve security and performance.

String sql="insert into employee values(?,?,?)";

PreparedStatement ps=con.prepareStatement(sql);

ps.setInt(1,101);

ps.setString(2,"Rahul");

ps.setDouble(3,45000);

ps.executeUpdate();

Advantages

Prevents SQL Injection
Faster for repeated execution
Easier to maintain
Industry standard
Common JDBC Interfaces
Interface	Purpose
DriverManager	Gets database connection
Connection	Represents DB connection
Statement	Executes static SQL
PreparedStatement	Executes parameterized SQL
CallableStatement	Calls stored procedures
ResultSet	Holds query results
